    <h2>
      The Song Of Death
    </h2>
<pre xml:space="preserve">     Tune—“Oran an aoig.”

     Scene—A Field of Battle. Time of the day—evening. The wounded
     and dying of the victorious army are supposed to join in the
     following song.
</pre>
<pre xml:space="preserve">     Farewell, thou fair day, thou green earth, and ye skies,
     Now gay with the broad setting sun;
     Farewell, loves and friendships, ye dear tender ties,
     Our race of existence is run!
     Thou grim King of Terrors; thou Life's gloomy foe!
     Go, frighten the coward and slave;
     Go, teach them to tremble, fell tyrant! but know
     No terrors hast thou to the brave!

     Thou strik'st the dull peasant—he sinks in the dark,
     Nor saves e'en the wreck of a name;
     Thou strik'st the young hero—a glorious mark;
     He falls in the blaze of his fame!
     In the field of proud honour—our swords in our hands,
     Our King and our country to save;
     While victory shines on Life's last ebbing sands,—
     O! who would not die with the brave!
</pre>
